Computer Language: (("Teaching Languages" "How to Design Programs" "Advanced Student") (#(#t constructor repeating-decimal #t #t none) #f ((lib "cs019.rkt" "installed-teachpacks"))))
>Description:
Names and conventions matter.  People ask "How does one program in this language?", by which they also mean what the syntactic conventions are.  This includes indentation, all-close-parens-on-one-line, and caps.

Racket is not a CamelCase language; it just isn't, and making it so would require changing extensive numbers of primitives.  But signatures are a new thing, and they're not used in all conventional value positions, so they could have their own rules.  Unfortunately, they are already in a confused state.

Right now signatures have TWO conventions:

- For defined structures, use the name of the struct.
- For pre-defined signatures, use init caps (String, Number, etc).

These two are inconsistent.  Forcing people to capitalize the names of structure definitions is not straightforward either, because it makes the rest of the code very ugly:

(define-struct Cow (a b))
(make-Cow 1 2)

is not conventional-looking, either.  Worse, we currently have two different defaults already, because String and Number are caps (so they "look" like signatures), but posn is not (so it doesn't).

I'd like to suggest that signature definitions be automatically init-capitalized unless they already have an init cap (in which case we leave the caps alone, since they might be CamelCased).  Of course, this requires knowing when a signature binding is taking place.  But having used signatures for a week now,  I find the current system far too ugly to look at, and hard to explain to students.
>How-To-Repeat:
>Fix:
>Audit-Trail:
