 I wondered about that, specifically, what char-upcase does.  It says
 
   Produces a character consistent with the 1-to-1 code point mapping
 defined by Unicode. If char has no upcase mapping, char-upcase
 produces char.
 
 So I guess this isn't really a solution...
 
