Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11210: signatures need to decide on capitalization
Date: Tue, 14 Sep 2010 12:32:38 -0400

 [[ I dislike the use of bug reports for feature discussions. ]]
 
 I struggled with this problem as soon as checked signatures 'slipped' =
 into the code base for HtDP, long before Shriram started throwing them =
 at his class. (I know I am brave, I would never have been that brave.)=20=
 
 
 There are even more problems than have been mentioned. In=20
 
  (define-struct s (f g h))
 
 s can serve as some syntax-info repository
 s can serve as the name of the signature=20
 s can serve as a constructor name=20
 
 Plus *sl struct defs have their own definitions. They aren't really =
 plain Racket structs.=20
 
 ;; ---=20
 
 Here is my idea: I think we should introduce a checked define-struct. =
 Perhaps we could just use a ";" or a "/c" to indicate that the =
 define-struct is different. In addition, I would ask students to =
 introduce a separate name for the signature. For example,=20
 
  (define-struct: s ({f : Number} {g : String}) : Address)=20
 
 would introduce a struct that combines a Number and a String into an =
 Address. That would scale to Typed Racket and we might even be able to =
 reuse its parser. It avoids the silly-looking and typing-intensive =
 specification of constructors, selectors, and predicates. This also =
 leaves us free to use=20
 
  (s 42 "hello")
 
 to construct instances and eliminates other notational problems.=20
 
 
 
From: Shriram Krishnamurthi <sk@cs.brown.edu>
To: Matthias Felleisen <matthias@ccs.neu.edu>
Cc: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>,
        Sam Tobin-Hochstadt <samth@ccs.neu.edu>, bugs@racket-lang.org,
        nobody@racket-lang.org, bug-notification@racket-lang.org
Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11210: signatures need to decide on capitalization
Date: Tue, 14 Sep 2010 14:37:25 -0400

 > [[ I dislike the use of bug reports for feature discussions. ]]
 
 Understood.  I explained why I did so.
 
 > Here is my idea: I think we should introduce a checked
 > define-struct. Perhaps we could just use a ";" or a "/c" to indicate
 > that the define-struct is different.
 
 I sure hope that's a typo, and you meant ":", not ";".
 
 I do not like the DMdA style of making all the names explicit, so we
 can agree on that.  Interestingly, I did show my students
 
 (define-struct foo (bar baz))
 (: make-foo (Number Number -> String))
 (: foo-bar (foo -> Number))
 etc.
 
 and they seem to have picked up on it.  That is, they don't mind
 enumerating the names for the purpose of giving them contracts,
 especially since the contracts are checked.  But writing out all the
 structures in full would not fly, even less so in Bootstrap (where
 time is limited and students are not expert typists).
 
 >  =A0(define-struct: s ({f : Number} {g : String}) : Address)
 >
 > would introduce a struct that combines a Number and a String into an Addr=
 ess. That would scale to Typed Racket and we might even be able to reuse it=
 s parser. It avoids the silly-looking and typing-intensive specification of=
  constructors, selectors, and predicates. This also leaves us free to use
 >
 >  =A0(s 42 "hello")
 >
 > to construct instances and eliminates other notational problems.
 
 I LIKE THIS!
 
 I presume, in many cases, we will have
 
 (define-struct: <constructor name> <field-spec> <CamelCaseVersionOfConstruc=
 tor>)
 
 as in
 
 (define-struct posn ({x : Number} {y : Number}) : Posn)
 
 I'm glad you are stating consistency w/ TR as a principle.  Can we do
 the same for "type" variables also?  Right now TR lists them
 explicitly as variables, whereas because signatures don't have a
 binding form, it uses the %a, %b, ... convention.  I'd rather they did
 the same thing (reusing parsers, again, is great), and personally I
 prefer the TR notation to having to explain where %a, ... came from.
 
 Shriram
