Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11210: signatures need to decide on capitalization
Date: Tue, 14 Sep 2010 15:00:37 -0400

 On the contrary, I think it's very valuable to get students to
 understand that what they *want* to write is
 
 (: all ((%a -> %b) (list-of %a) -> (list-of %b)))
 
 but all they *can* write is
 
 (: all ((Any -> Any) (list-of Any) -> (list-of Any)))
 
 and then show them that when they go to Typed Racket, the previous
 contract (syntactically modified) will not only work but also do the
 right thing, so they get more enforcement power (for now).
 
 This is an important teaching moment, and not a good time to have to
 field questions like, "If it only does Any, why does it let me write
 %a and %b as if they are being checked for consistency?"
 
 The comment analogy doesn't work for me, either.  To me,
 
 ; foo: ...
 
 is still meant to represent truth.
 
 Shriram
From: Michael Sperber <sperber@deinprogramm.de>
To: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>
Cc: Shriram Krishnamurthi <sk@cs.brown.edu>,
        Matthias Felleisen <matthias@ccs.neu.edu>,
        Sam Tobin-Hochstadt <samth@ccs.neu.edu>, bugs@racket-lang.org,
        nobody@racket-lang.org, bug-notification@racket-lang.org
Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11210: signatures need to decide on capitalization
Date: Wed, 15 Sep 2010 09:08:50 +0200

 Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu> writes:
 
 > I think that Mike considers these to be akin to comments in
 > documentation, ie useful annotations to have right inline. Enough
 > utility and enough pain to try to put comments there that it is worth
 > it to have multiple names for "any" in this context. (Speaking
 > pedagogically.)
 
 Having different type variables allows you to talk about signatures of
 things like fold, where two different type variables occur.  The
 difference is not checked, but the discussion is meaningful, and quite
 successful with the students.  (I.e. many can properly write signatures
 with different type variables.)  The underlying idea is, of course, that
 when switching to a type system, the difference becomes meaningful.
 
 -- 
 Cheers =8-} Mike
 Friede, Völkerverständigung und überhaupt blabla
