Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11210: signatures need to decide on capitalization
Date: Wed, 15 Sep 2010 09:47:11 -0400

 Let me clarify this a bit.  Why would my students even know this is
 broken?  A handful would try it out themselves.  But it is also
 precisely my teaching (and writing) style to ask them to write the
 broken versions and to see what happens.
 
 I like teaching in Racket because broken things report as broken:
 
   (+ 1 true)
 
 is not 2, it's an error; and things that shouldn't be broken aren't:
 
   (expt 2 10000)
 
 doesn't give a small negative number, or something like that.
 
 Of course, there are static and there are dynamic errors.  This is
 something we not only have a good account of, our account grows better
 and better (nothing -> contracts -> types, all demonstrable within the
 "same" language, more-or-less).  This is really important, core,
 computer science stuff, and we get to teach it to froshes.
 
 The "contract variable" mechanism breaks neither statically nor
 dynamically even when there is an error.  To me, that's a bug.
 
 Furthermore, this principle of removing those bugs that other
 languages have and teach about is one of THE most important things
 that attracts people to teaching with Racket.  We would be making a
 grave error to not recognize and sustain that.
 
 Shriram
