Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11210: signatures need to decide on capitalization
Date: Thu, 16 Sep 2010 06:49:10 -0400

 I wish it were that simple.  The whole point of the course is that we
 can offer a *counter-point* to the brokenness of the world:
 
 http://www.cs.brown.edu/courses/cs019/2010/readme
 
 It's fine to say "This year we're using something highly experimental,
 so things won't work quite as expected" -- we did that with phones
 last year, we're doing it with your contracts this year, and the
 students are great about rolling with the punches.  But brokenness in
 the language is another thing.
 
 Let me offer a concrete proposal.
 
 1. Add an Any contract (trivial?) that has the same syntax and intent
 as that of Typed Racket.
 
 2. In the docs for %a or whatever you decide to call it (in fact, if
 the semantics is different from that of TR, maybe a different syntax
 is the RIGHT thing!), explicitly say that these don't work.  Right now
 the docs do not say that, and surely you can agree that at least
 *that* is a true problem.
 
 I have some students who are very adventurous about looking up and
 trying things.  They deserve a warning that this notation doesn't
 actually do any enforcing.
 
 These two changes will be plenty enough to accomplish my curricular
 goals, while seemingly being compatible with yours.
 
 Shriram


